WEBVTT



00:00:20.704 --> 00:00:26.528
It's said that when God rescued us through Jesus, He didn't just connect us to a head, but to a body as well.

00:00:26.528 --> 00:00:28.512
He didn't just connect us to himself.

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:30.240
He connected us to one another.

00:00:30.272 --> 00:00:33.344
That's why the relationships in this group are so important.

00:00:33.152 --> 00:00:40.320
They give you the opportunity to find perspective on what it means to trust and obey God in the context of your everyday life.

00:00:40.288 --> 00:00:43.136
This is community with insiders.

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:49.696
Tonight, Clay Scroggins is going to unpack how the relationships in this group can be different from the other relationships in your life.

00:00:49.568 --> 00:00:57.184
And then some of our group leaders are going to give you specific, actual examples of how they've seen community with insiders play out.

00:01:07.136 --> 00:01:11.936
Can you imagine a baseball team leaving first base unattended?

00:01:12.256 --> 00:01:14.112
They would never do that.

00:01:14.016 --> 00:01:18.144
Because that's an extremely important position for every team.

00:01:18.048 --> 00:01:24.320
See, they would never say, "You know what? We got Fred over there and he's good, but he's just not a great fielder."

00:01:24.256 --> 00:01:29.152
And then we got Bob over there who's just he's a good hitter but he's just a little too chatty.

00:01:29.152 --> 00:01:32.192
So we're just going to leave the position open.

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:33.664
No, they would never do that.

00:01:33.536 --> 00:01:39.072
Because they wouldn't want to face the consequences of leaving such an important position.

00:01:39.008 --> 00:01:40.320
unattended.

00:01:40.512 --> 00:01:43.392
Yet people do that in life all the time.

00:01:43.584 --> 00:01:49.024
In fact, my wife and I met with a marriage counselor, a great friend of ours a couple of years ago, who said, "You know what?

00:01:48.704 --> 00:01:52.064
If you guys aren't careful, you have the propensity

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:54.880
To leave first base open in your life.

00:01:54.880 --> 00:02:04.928
Because all of us lean towards, we all gravitate towards moving towards isolation. And if we're not careful, we'll leave an extremely important relationship at

00:02:04.448 --> 00:02:05.792
In our life.

00:02:05.824 --> 00:02:07.104
Unattended.

00:02:07.008 --> 00:02:10.336
You know what first base is for you? First base is that couple.

00:02:10.144 --> 00:02:12.064
That you can depend on.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.512
First base is that guy that you can call when things aren't going your way.

00:02:16.448 --> 00:02:18.208
First base is the

00:02:18.016 --> 00:02:22.720
The couple that you can call when it's Friday night and you just want to grab a pizza with somebody.

00:02:23.200 --> 00:02:28.416
And all of us need someone on first base in our lives.

00:02:31.904 --> 00:02:39.968
Even though God wired us to need community, we live in a world that pushes us further and further into isolation. Our culture

00:02:39.808 --> 00:02:49.856
drives us towards isolation. There's a guy named Robert Putnam who wrote a book a number of years ago that showed since the 1970s that our culture has been on the decline.

00:02:49.376 --> 00:02:59.424
When it comes to people engaging in social activity, playing recreational leagues, and it's not just true as far as our social engagement in the community, it's also true

00:02:58.944 --> 00:03:01.824
In the way we engage in social media.

00:03:01.920 --> 00:03:06.944
These discoveries in social media were meant to connect us to others, but

00:03:06.592 --> 00:03:10.048
In one sense, they actually, we find ourselves

00:03:09.888 --> 00:03:13.856
Sitting in front of our phone or sitting in front of our computer

00:03:13.856 --> 00:03:17.056
Isolated more than we are connected.

00:03:16.992 --> 00:03:22.272
One of the interesting things about our culture is the invention of the garage door.

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:32.928
It's just natural tendency for us to live in our subdivisions and just pull right into our garage while waving at our neighbor, watching the door close behind us, closing us off.

00:03:32.448 --> 00:03:34.496
Off to a relationship.

00:03:34.304 --> 00:03:39.136
And unfortunately, that's just not the way God wired us to live.

00:03:40.352 --> 00:03:44.544
See, throughout Scripture, we see the steam of a team, right?

00:03:44.256 --> 00:03:47.232
The same way that a team is dependent upon each other.

00:03:47.008 --> 00:03:48.224
For

00:03:48.064 --> 00:03:52.288
Each individual person's growth, but also for the team growth.

00:03:52.384 --> 00:04:02.432
God actually gave us an amazing metaphor to explain this through the apostle Paul. Paul wrote a letter called 1 Corinthians and in 1 Corinthians Paul gives us this illustration here.

00:04:01.952 --> 00:04:10.208
He says that we are like a body. We meaning the church, the body of Christ. And he uses that word very strategically.

00:04:09.824 --> 00:04:13.504
Because in the same way a body has different parts,

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:17.792
That each function differently and in a sense function individually

00:04:17.632 --> 00:04:20.608
He says those parts are very interdependent.

00:04:20.448 --> 00:04:30.496
upon each other. He says the hand would never say to the foot, "I don't need you. I could just live without you." He says, "No, that would be foolish. That would be ridiculous." And the same thing

00:04:30.016 --> 00:04:32.736
So in the same way, the foot would never say that to the hand, right?

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:40.576
Because the parts of the body are meant to work together to help the overall body but also to help each part individually.

00:04:40.832 --> 00:04:47.648
And the same is true for you and the same is true for me, that God's plan to grow you is probably through someone else.

00:04:47.488 --> 00:04:51.648
And God's plan to grow someone else is probably through you.

00:04:51.840 --> 00:05:01.888
And this group that you're sitting in right now is a wonderful opportunity for you to allow God to do something great. But it's going to be when you do something that

00:05:01.408 --> 00:05:05.248
Something as well it's going to be when you step out and say you know what

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:15.168
I'm going to be a part of this group and I may or may not find my first basement, but I'm stepping into a wonderful opportunity where God might just use the people around me to grow me.

00:05:14.688 --> 00:05:18.880
And God might also use you to grow the people around you.

00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:26.784
So we want you to do just a couple of things. We'll make it really simple, really easy. We want you to just show up to group, which you've already done that.

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:29.504
We want you to join in. We want you to...

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:37.472
to take the initiative to say, "Hey, look, I'm gonna join in the conversation. I'm gonna join in the lives of these people around me."

00:05:37.504 --> 00:05:39.968
And then the last thing is we want you to be real.

00:05:39.744 --> 00:05:44.064
We want you to be honest about your life, to be authentic about your life.

00:05:43.936 --> 00:05:48.384
It doesn't mean you've got to spill all your deepest, darkest secrets.

00:05:48.128 --> 00:05:55.648
But it does mean that when the time is right that you can be vulnerable about your life, that you can be authentic and real and true.

00:05:55.392 --> 00:05:58.560
About who you are and about what's going on in your life.

00:05:58.816 --> 00:06:04.832
And when you do that, you're going to find that God really has wired you to enjoy your life.

00:06:04.736 --> 00:06:07.968
When it's lived in community with others.

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:32.512
The misconception is that group is Monday night.

00:06:32.256 --> 00:06:38.976
From five to seven you know it's kind of like anything that you do that is the the time and investment that you put into it so

00:06:39.072 --> 00:06:42.880
Taking the time to invest in relationships makes group

00:06:42.624 --> 00:06:44.576
I'm so much more meaningful.

00:06:44.352 --> 00:06:52.224
I think that when people start to take the initiative, like you said, it starts to build a strengthening community.

00:06:52.064 --> 00:07:00.096
On the night of small group and outside of small group, which is really what community is, and I've been surprised just how much just.

00:06:59.968 --> 00:07:07.776
Talking with somebody and seeing them outside of group really can strengthen those relationships, because then you wouldn't think that talking to somebody,

00:07:07.648 --> 00:07:12.800
twice a week as opposed to once a week would change that much. But we found that it really does.

00:07:12.704 --> 00:07:14.208
When you sign up,

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:21.216
You say, "I'm pretty much committed to be here." And, you know, everybody gets the sense that you are.

00:07:21.056 --> 00:07:24.224
There are vacations, there are illnesses.

00:07:24.512 --> 00:07:25.536
But...

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:30.048
We have been in groups where people have not come for...

00:07:29.888 --> 00:07:32.576
Far lesser reasons

00:07:32.448 --> 00:07:34.240
The nose and

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:38.976
Fairly inconsequential reasons and when that happens

00:07:38.816 --> 00:07:41.184
You get a sense that if

00:07:40.992 --> 00:07:42.048
They don't.

00:07:41.824 --> 00:07:49.216
care, then almost like, why should you care? And all of a sudden, the times that you have the necessary quorum,

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:50.400
Become less

00:07:50.144 --> 00:07:55.200
So you tend to meet less. So this is like a rolling stone bed effect.

00:07:54.976 --> 00:08:01.504
One kind of misconception I think a lot of people have is that they think when I don't show up for group that night it just affects me.

00:08:01.184 --> 00:08:11.232
that I'm not getting anything out of group or I didn't get anything out of group last week and I had a rough day at work today so I'm just gonna stay at home tonight. You have no idea

00:08:10.752 --> 00:08:11.968
idea what

00:08:11.744 --> 00:08:14.368
Just showing up and being there.

00:08:13.952 --> 00:08:19.584
really will do. I think there's a misconception sometimes about men in small groups.

00:08:19.552 --> 00:08:26.080
And I think often people come in as guys to be much more guarded and much more walls up.

00:08:25.888 --> 00:08:30.304
Some of the coolest things that I've seen in our small group is when we were able to

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:33.536
Break those walls down and your faith

00:08:33.376 --> 00:08:36.032
And God grows because you know

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:37.280
That you're loved

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:39.520
You know that people care about you.

00:08:39.392 --> 00:08:44.032
But you also know on the flip side of that that someone's going to hold you accountable.

00:08:44.672 --> 00:08:47.648
I think one thing for us that we found in groups is

00:08:47.936 --> 00:08:50.240
There's a huge difference between

00:08:50.080 --> 00:09:00.128
If people are really vulnerable when they share their stories at first, how quickly everyone just seems to really bond. Even if your personalities are different or your life stories are completely different.

00:08:59.648 --> 00:09:00.896
different I think.

00:09:00.864 --> 00:09:05.856
You just bond because you're open and honest with each other and feel more comfortable sharing with other people.

00:09:05.824 --> 00:09:13.568
We had something go on where the group leader said, "Let's talk about..." and there was a very specific agenda about

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:17.248
How you met and how you got married and some of the high points.

00:09:16.992 --> 00:09:19.328
And then some of the low points.

00:09:19.424 --> 00:09:23.456
And there was a couple that started off that we knew fairly well.

00:09:23.488 --> 00:09:25.824
And it was about the most honest

00:09:25.696 --> 00:09:28.160
Transparent, emotional things.

00:09:27.936 --> 00:09:29.632
We've ever gone through.

00:09:29.504 --> 00:09:34.560
It's just great. It was just absolutely terrific. But it took one couple.

00:09:34.560 --> 00:09:40.832
And the guts of one couple to start it off so that the others could say if they're willing

00:09:40.704 --> 00:09:42.464
To talk about that.

00:09:42.400 --> 00:09:44.032
And indeed

00:09:43.904 --> 00:09:45.472
I can talk about.

00:09:45.248 --> 00:09:46.240
This.

00:09:46.944 --> 00:09:49.568
I think God has challenged us all to grow.

00:09:49.696 --> 00:09:52.928
But also to grow in a way that we grow together.

00:09:52.608 --> 00:09:54.720
And knowing that this is not a

00:09:54.496 --> 00:09:59.488
Just my relationship with God, but we grow together in our relationship with God.

00:10:00.160 --> 00:10:05.152
I feel like it helps help you see how big God actually is.

00:10:04.704 --> 00:10:14.752
Because sitting in a big church, sometimes it's difficult to see that what he's saying on the stage is impacting me, but I don't know what it's doing for me.

00:10:14.272 --> 00:10:24.320
for anyone else and so to sit across from people in a circle and say, "What did you think about that sermon?" or "What's God teaching you?" and to see that God is

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:26.944
And God's working in their heart just as well as yours. Amen.

00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:36.128
Makes God so much bigger. Small group got me, got my wife and I to forgive some relatives that hit the floor we hadn't talked to.

00:10:35.776 --> 00:10:37.376
For four or five years.

00:10:37.504 --> 00:10:39.008
Okay, I'm...

00:10:38.784 --> 00:10:40.064
I'll say i'm wrong.

00:10:40.128 --> 00:10:41.824
What do I lose?

00:10:41.696 --> 00:10:47.040
So I said I'm wrong and all of a sudden we have relationships with very close siblings.

00:10:47.008 --> 00:10:49.568
That hit the floor for five or six years we didn't do.

00:10:49.664 --> 00:10:51.104
Small group.

00:10:51.744 --> 00:10:53.792
Urged us to do that.

00:10:53.696 --> 00:11:01.728
so i i know there's growing faith in terms of understanding the bible these are growing applications of faith.

00:11:01.696 --> 00:11:05.792
